ncertainty surrounding Latinidad is emancipatory: by queering race—by upsetting assumptions about categories of human difference—Latinidad destabilizes the architecture of oppression. But Laura Grappo is less sanguine. She draws on case studies including the San Antonio Four (Latinas who were wrongfully accused of child sex abuse); the football star Aaron Hernandez’s incarceration and suicide; Lorena Bobbitt, the headline-grabbing Ecuadorian domestic-abuse survivor; and controversies over the racial identities of public Latinx figures to show how media institutions and state authorities deploy the ambiguities of Latinidad in ways that mystify the sources of Latinx political and economic disadvantage. With Latinidad always in a state of flux, it is all too easy for the powerful to conjure whatever phantoms serve their interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aHispanic American gaysxPress coveragezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aLatin AmericansxEthnic identityxPress coveragezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aLatin AmericansxPress coveragexPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aLatin AmericansxPress coveragezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aLatin AmericansxRace identityxPress coveragezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aLatin AmericanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aLatinidad, Queer Latinidad, queer studies, Latinx studies, sexuality, Queer latinidades, Latinidades, Gender Studies, cultural studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociolo